[49m[38;5;9m- 70    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Consent & Opt-out Management** | TCPA (Telephone Consumer Protection Act) compliance for voice and SMS: explicit prior written consent to send automated reminders to mobile numbers, documented STOP-keyword handling, and an opt-out database that is queried before every send. Email CAN-SPAM compliance is simpler but still mandatory: working unsubscribe link on every email, honored within 10 business days.  |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Consent & Opt-out Management** | TCPA compliance for voice and SMS requires careful posture. Healthcare appointment reminders from an existing provider qualify for the FCC healthcare exemption (47 CFR 64.1200(a)(3)(iv)), which permits automated calls/texts to residential and wireless numbers without prior express consent, provided the content is strictly limited to appointment reminders with no marketing, no billing collections, and no third-party content. However, many organizations capture prior written consent anyway as a defensive posture, because the exemption's narrow content scope is easy to accidentally violate (a "reminder" that mentions an outstanding copay or links to a patient portal with billing info may cross the line). Regardless of which posture you adopt, STOP-keyword handling and opt-out enforcement are required. Every inbound STOP reply must suppress future messages within a reasonable timeframe (carriers enforce this at the network level for short codes; for long codes and 10DLC, your opt-out database must be authoritative). Document your chosen posture and enforce it in code, not just policy. Email CAN-SPAM compliance is simpler but still mandatory: working unsubscribe link on every email, honored within 10 business days. |
