[49m[38;5;9m- 358     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - Very-low-volume patients (new to the practice, one or two prior visits): the bandit's personal posterior is too wide to be meaningful, and the decision is effectively driven by the cohort prior. This is fine, but don't expect meaningful personalization in the first few interactions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Very-low-volume patients (new to the practice, one or two prior visits): the bandit's personal posterior is too wide to be meaningful, and the decision is effectively driven by the cohort prior. This is fine, but don't expect meaningful personalization in the first few interactions. A more precise framing: a typical primary care patient has 1-3 appointments per year, accumulating only a handful of per-channel observations annually. Reaching ~50 observations per (patient, channel) for a reasonably tight posterior would take 15-50 years at that frequency. Most patients will never move off the cohort prior for individual personalization. The bandit's real value at fleet scale is efficient cohort-level learning (the system quickly learns which channels work best for patient segments) plus high-frequency-patient personalization (patients with chronic conditions who visit monthly accumulate enough data within a year). If per-patient personalization is the primary goal across all patients, a hierarchical or partial-pooling bandit formulation (where individual arms share strength with cohort-level arms) is worth evaluating.
