[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Fairness monitoring that someone actually looks at.** The architecture emits `reminder_reward` metrics sliced by cohort. That data has to flow into a dashboard that a human reviews on a regular cadence. "No one reviewed the cohort dashboard for six months and SMS response for our over-65 population quietly dropped to 40%" is the kind of operational drift that destroys trust in the system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dead-letter queues for failed dispatches.** The architecture as drawn has no durable sink when things fail. Add an SQS dead-letter queue on the EventBridge Scheduler target configuration for the recommender Lambda. Without it, if the recommender Lambda fails after exhausting Scheduler's retry attempts, the reminder event is silently lost. No reminder is sent, no record exists of the failure. Similarly, add an on-failure destination (SQS or SNS) on the Kinesis event source mapping that invokes the reward-updater Lambda, so failed reward computations land somewhere observable rather than disappearing. Set CloudWatch alarms on DLQ depth (any message in the DLQ is worth investigating; threshold of 1 is appropriate). The replay runbook: when messages land in the DLQ, an operator inspects the payload, identifies the failure cause (transient error vs. bad data vs. missing patient), fixes the root cause, and replays the messages by re-driving from the DLQ back to the original target. For reminders, timeliness matters: a reminder DLQ message older than the appointment itself should be discarded, not replayed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Confirmation URL security.** The `confirm_url` in the pseudocode uses a reminder-ID UUID in the path, unauthenticated. That UUID travels through SMS gateways, email servers, third-party URL shorteners, and lock-screen previews on potentially shared devices. Risks: URL guessing (UUIDs are 128-bit, so brute-force is infeasible, but the link is visible to anyone with physical access to the device), link leakage through intermediaries, and the fact that confirmation pages that display clinical detail create a PHI exposure if someone else clicks the link. Mitigations: use single-use, time-limited tokens (not long-lived reminder IDs) as the URL parameter, so the link expires after first use or after a few hours. If you use a URL shortener, it must be an internal or BAA-covered service (not bit.ly or similar third-party services that log click metadata). The confirmation page should not display clinical detail beyond what the reminder itself contained (provider name and appointment time, not diagnosis or procedure).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EventBridge Scheduler account quotas.** EventBridge Scheduler has default account-level quotas: 1,000,000 active schedules and TPS limits on schedule creation and deletion. These become real design constraints at scale. A mid-size health system with 100,000 appointments per month and four reminder offsets per appointment produces 400,000 active schedules. That's approaching half the default quota with no room for growth. Request quota increases proactively when deployment is sized. Use schedule groups (one per department or clinic) for operational management, monitoring, and bulk cleanup. For very large deployments (500K+ monthly appointments), evaluate whether a DynamoDB-backed custom scheduler (scan for due items on a cadence) is more cost-effective and quota-free compared to Scheduler. The tradeoff: Scheduler handles retries and time-zone math for you; a custom solution puts that on your plate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reserved concurrency on the recommender Lambda.** The recommender experiences a sharp fan-out spike at common offsets. When you schedule reminders at T-24h, every appointment tomorrow morning gets its reminder fired within a narrow window (all appointments at 9 AM tomorrow fire their T-24h reminder at 9 AM today). In a shared-account Lambda environment, unrelated workloads can consume concurrency and starve the reminder pipeline during this spike. Set reserved concurrency on the recommender Lambda (sized to your peak expected fan-out) so reminder dispatch is protected from noisy neighbors. Monitor the `ConcurrentExecutions` metric and alert when utilization exceeds 80% of reserved capacity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cohort prior loading and refresh.** The pseudocode references `lookup_cohort()` and `COHORT_PRIORS` but doesn't specify how priors are loaded into the Lambda at runtime. In production: cohort priors are computed offline (monthly or quarterly) from historical reminder outcomes, aggregated by cohort bucket (age band, visit type, prior engagement level). They're stored in a small DynamoDB table keyed by cohort identifier. The recommender Lambda reads this table into module-level memory on cold start (a single Query that returns a few dozen rows). A scheduled Lambda or Step Functions workflow refreshes the priors on the configured cadence. Two important constraints: (1) enforce a k-anonymity threshold on cohort size (e.g., minimum 50 patients per cohort bucket) so that priors don't leak PHI about small groups; (2) log the refresh timestamp and version so you can trace which prior was active for any given reminder decision.
